question or "crux" deduplication within each round so you don't get asked the same thing over and over again










Idea: for each conversation, have the initial LLM pass come up with something like this:

p_u(y | x, user context)    => this is what you're already having it estimate

A list of cruxes c_i which can resolve to c_i = 1 or c_i = 0 (assuming binary, could be more complex)
For each crux:
p(c_i = 1 | user context)   => probability you think the user will resolve the crux one way or another
p_u(y = 1 | x, user context, c_i = 0)    => updated probability that the user would label as 1 given the crux is resolved negatively
p_u(y = 1 | x, user context, c_i = 1)     => updated probability that the user would label as 1 given the crux is resolved positively

Then based on this, you can cluster cruxes and rank them based on overall information gain

IG(c) = sum_x H[p_u(y | x)] - p(c_i = 1) H[ p_u(y | x, c_i = 1) ] - p(c_i = 0) H[ p_u(y | x, c_i = 0) ]

So this ends up capturing both:

Does this crux come up across a bunch of transcripts
Would resolving the crux reduce the label uncertainty a lot across those transcripts
